        <h3>Types of Mitigation Systems</h3>
        <p><strong>Active Soil Depressurization (ASD):</strong> The most common method, using a fan to draw radon from beneath the foundation.</p>
        <p><strong>Passive Systems:</strong> Rely on natural air pressure differences, often used in new construction.</p>
        <p><strong>Crawl Space Ventilation:</strong> For homes with crawl spaces, increasing air circulation to reduce radon buildup.</p>
        <p><strong>Sump Pump Systems:</strong> Sealing and venting sump pump systems that can be radon entry points.</p>

        <h3>System Components</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Radon Fan:</strong> High-quality, continuous-duty fans designed for 24/7 operation</li>
          <li><strong>PVC Piping:</strong> Durable piping system to transport radon gas safely outside</li>
          <li><strong>Manometer:</strong> Monitoring device to ensure system is functioning properly</li>
          <li><strong>Warning Labels:</strong> Required safety labels and system identification</li>
          <li><strong>Electrical Components:</strong> Proper electrical connections and safety switches</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Effectiveness and Maintenance</h3>
        <p>Professional radon mitigation systems are highly effective, typically reducing radon levels by 80–99%. Most systems reduce levels to below 2.0 pCi/L.</p>

        <div style="background:#f8f9fa;padding:20px;border-radius:10px;margin:20px 0;">
          <h4>System Maintenance:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Check manometer monthly to ensure proper operation</li>
            <li>Listen for fan operation (should run continuously)</li>
            <li>Annual professional inspection recommended</li>
            <li>Post-mitigation testing within 30 days of installation</li>
            <li>Re-test every 2 years to ensure continued effectiveness</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Cost and Energy Efficiency</h3>
        <p>Radon mitigation systems are designed for continuous operation with minimal energy consumption. Most systems use less electricity than a 100-watt light bulb, costing approximately $3–7 per month to operate.</p>

